metrics_conclusion: In terms of chords and melody, Insight is significantly more complex than the typical song, having above average scores in Chord Complexity, Melodic Complexity, Chord-Melody Tension, Chord Progression Novelty and Chord-Bass Melody.
key_conclusion:
Insight is written in the key of A Minor.  

According to the Theorytab database, it is the most popular key among Minor keys and     the 7th most popular  among all keys. Minor keys, along with major keys, are a common choice for popular music.  The three most important chords, built off the 1st, 4th and 5th scale degrees are all minor chords (A minor, D minor, and E minor).

metadata.editComments: Fixed the melody a bit, and am pretty sure I got that part right. Tweaked the chords some, and that part I'm quite a bit less sure of. They sound pretty good, but could use a second opinion.

Changed i6 chords to III chords because of the G naturals. In the first one, the arpeggio outlines a CMaj(add9) and the second outlines a CMaj7. I also think that the bV should really be the tritone substitution of the IV chord, something like V43b5/IV. But HookTheory doesn't allow b5's yet so we can't really accurately describe tritone substitutions. Hopefully someday.
another part added. love this song so much.

Small chord changes to reflect bass notes. I7 changed to V7/iv because it more accurately reflects its function. I feel as though the vii should really be iv/iv, which makes a lot of sense as it would be a iv-V-i in the key of the iv. But Hooktheory only supports IV/x for some reason, as if secondary subdominants can't be minor. It makes sense that secondary dominants can only be major, because the minor v chord doesn't contain a leading tone. But subdominant function chords can be major or minor and it doesn't really affect function at all (i.e. you could have IV go to V go to one OR iv go to V go to one in either major or minor. They both work in both.) Hopefully someday in the future Hooktheory implements this.
